<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<handout>
  <title>Worksheet 5.3, Diagonalization</title>

  <ul marker="">

    <!-- Problem 1 -->
    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(1) &#160; Recall from lecture: a matrix <m>A</m> is diagonalizable if it can be written as <m>A = PDP^{-1}</m>.</p>

      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li><p><m>P</m> is a matrix whose columns are __________________.</p></li>
        <li><p><m>D</m> is a __________________ matrix.</p></li>
        <li><p>The elements on the main diagonal of <m>D</m> are __________________.</p></li>
        <li><p>A diagonal matrix is a matrix that __________________.</p></li>
        <li><p>The geometric multiplicity of an eigenvalue is _____________________________________.</p></li>
        <li><p>A matrix can be diagonalized when the geometric multiplicities of all eigenvalues _______________________________________________.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </li>

    <!-- Problem 2 -->
    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(2) &#160; If possible, construct <m>P</m> and <m>D</m> so that <m>A = PDP^{-1}</m>. Eigenvalues of <m>A</m> are given.</p>

      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>
            A =
            \begin{pmatrix}
              3 &amp; 1 &amp; 1 \\
              1 &amp; 3 &amp; 1 \\
              1 &amp; 1 &amp; 3
            \end{pmatrix},
            \quad
            \lambda = 2, 2, 5
            </m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>
            A =
            \begin{pmatrix}
              1 &amp; 3 \\
              4 &amp; 2
            \end{pmatrix},
            \quad
            \lambda = -2, 5
            </m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>
            A =
            \begin{pmatrix}
              3 &amp; 2 \\
              0 &amp; 3
            \end{pmatrix},
            \quad
            \lambda = 3, 3
            </m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </li>

</ul>
<ul marker="">

    <!-- Problem 3 -->
    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(3) &#160; If possible, give an example of:</p>

      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li><p>a singular <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix in echelon form that can be diagonalized.</p></li>
        <li><p>a singular <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix in echelon form that cannot be diagonalized.</p></li>
        <li><p>an invertible <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix in echelon form that can be diagonalized.</p></li>
        <li><p>an invertible <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix in echelon form that cannot be diagonalized.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </li>

    <!-- Problem 4 -->
    <li workspace="1in">
      <p>(4) &#160; Indicate whether the statements are true or false.</p>

      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li><p>If <m>A</m> is diagonalizable, then so is <m>A^2</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>If <m>A^2</m> is diagonalizable, then so is <m>A</m>.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </li>

    <!-- Problem 5 -->
    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(5) &#160; Give an example of an upper triangular <m>4 \times 4</m> matrix <m>A</m> such that <m>0</m> is its only eigenvalue and its eigenspace is <m>3</m>-dimensional.
      Explain why the eigenspace has dimension <m>3</m>.</p>
    </li>

  </ul>
</handout>